{
  "text": "These results are easily rationalized by the architecture of the ribozyme, and show further how this architecture encodes cooperativity between tertiary interaction motifs. Although the A-minor interaction in P6 and the two peripheral TL-TR motifs (L2 and L9) are each coupled to the TH, they form independently of each other in I C (DDG link $0) ( Figure 5B ). Each TL-TR motif bridges a different domain interface, and these peripheral interactions can be expected to form independently. By contrast, docking either TL with its receptor depends greatly on the orientation of the P4-P6 and P3-P9 domains established by the TH [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , which is in turn stabilized by the TL-TR interactions [CITATION_3] . Therefore, the peripheral and core tertiary interactions mutually reinforce each other, producing the thermodynamic cooperativity that we observe.",
  "correct_citation": {
